1
00:00:31,856 --> 00:00:32,737
Good evening.

2
00:00:32,898 --> 00:00:34,820
I trust you had a fruitful day.

3
00:00:34,840 --> 00:00:38,183
I do not say happy, though I hope it has been happy.

4
00:00:39,104 --> 00:00:47,594
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sambodasa.

5
00:00:47,613 --> 00:00:55,823
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sambodasa.

6
00:00:56,426 --> 00:01:24,121
homage to the buddha the blessed noble and fully self-awakened one very good so uh we shall uh just finish off the taints uh i just

7
00:01:24,388 --> 00:01:32,677
As a last reminder, just in case you've forgotten, there are taints.

8
00:01:32,817 --> 00:01:34,058
Now, what are the taints again?

9
00:01:34,099 --> 00:01:47,572
They are all the sensual desires, all the senses, the longing to keep living, to become, and ignorance, which often manifests as wrong view.

10
00:01:48,033 --> 00:01:52,016
And remember that wrong views is often listed with ignorance.

11
00:01:52,957 --> 00:02:20,652
so there are tanks that should be abandoned by seeing so that's your insight uh through vipassana and specifically around not self so that first one will take you directly to full liberation the next one by restraining and then by using and then by enduring and avoiding and removing all those will certainly help but they will not lead to full and entire liberation

12
00:02:21,275 --> 00:02:26,602
But the last one will, which remember, is the development of the seven factors of enlightenment.

13
00:02:26,622 --> 00:02:33,170
So the first and the last, number one and number seven, are the ones to remember more.

14
00:02:33,831 --> 00:02:42,944
But remember that as soon as you see something coming into your heart, into your mind, which is unwholesome,

15
00:02:43,381 --> 00:02:51,729
jump on it and then reflect and say, now which one of these wonderful techniques the Buddha has given us is to be used here?

16
00:02:52,872 --> 00:02:58,016
And that way we'll find ourselves becoming more pure of heart, pure of heart.

17
00:02:59,558 --> 00:03:01,020
Okay, so we went through all that.

18
00:03:01,080 --> 00:03:02,382
It's taken us a while, but that's good.

19
00:03:03,623 --> 00:03:06,586
So I just want to read the last paragraph, the conclusion.

20
00:03:09,655 --> 00:03:14,520
So, well, he goes through it, all the things that I've just said.

21
00:03:14,539 --> 00:03:18,924
And then let me get the...

22
00:03:18,984 --> 00:03:20,485
It's a very long sentence.

23
00:03:21,265 --> 00:03:21,706
That's right.

24
00:03:21,766 --> 00:03:33,578
And when the taint had been abandoned by all the seven that we've mentioned, then he is called a bhikkhu who lives restrained with the restraint of all the taints.

25
00:03:34,479 --> 00:03:38,902
He has severed craving, flung off the fetters,

26
00:03:39,372 --> 00:03:45,039
And with complete penetration of conceit, he's made an end of suffering.

27
00:03:45,600 --> 00:03:48,824
So that's somebody who's finally completed the path.

28
00:03:49,787 --> 00:03:59,120
And of course, as usual, the bhikkhus are very satisfied and delighted in the Buddha's words, the Blessed One's words.

29
00:03:59,139 --> 00:04:07,692
So a severed craving, see, that's the end of those wrong desires based on seeking happiness in the sensual world.

30
00:04:08,228 --> 00:04:15,135
He's flung off the fetters, and that's what we're going to look at this evening, and his complete penetration of conceit.

31
00:04:15,316 --> 00:04:19,161
In other words, that whole sense of self has disappeared.

32
00:04:21,923 --> 00:04:28,170
So remember, self in this sense is identity with what we're experiencing, an identity.

33
00:04:30,293 --> 00:04:36,261
So we shall now move to number 64, which is the Mahamalunkya Putta.

34
00:04:36,730 --> 00:04:37,990
Malunkya Sauta.

35
00:04:38,011 --> 00:04:40,995
So it's the great discourse to Malunkya Putta.

36
00:04:42,196 --> 00:04:48,682
Often it would seem people were named the son of their mother.

37
00:04:48,822 --> 00:04:54,668
So this is the son of Malunkya Putta, of Malunkya, the Sari Putta, the son of Sari.

38
00:04:55,028 --> 00:05:01,235
So I suppose in those days, instead of saying Johnson, you would say Jameson and then you'd know who you were.

39
00:05:04,422 --> 00:05:11,028
So the Buddha's back in Saviti, that, remember, is his favorite place, and Arthapindika's parked there.

40
00:05:12,571 --> 00:05:20,600
The local king, Pasenadi of Kosala, I think I'm right, yes, Kosala, he was a great supporter.

41
00:05:23,062 --> 00:05:28,387
So now he asks the venerable Malonkya Putta,

42
00:05:28,822 --> 00:05:32,067
Do you remember the five lower fetters taught by me?

43
00:05:32,528 --> 00:05:34,291
I suppose before I go into the...

44
00:05:35,673 --> 00:05:37,375
I ought to just go through them very quickly.

45
00:05:38,057 --> 00:05:42,363
So the first one is an identity, a belief in identity, that's a self.

46
00:05:43,846 --> 00:05:44,848
Skeptical doubt.

47
00:05:47,552 --> 00:05:56,906
Remember that skeptical doubt isn't the wonder, the honest doubt, the desiring to know for oneself, right?

48
00:05:57,189 --> 00:05:59,774
which is based on I wonder if it's true.

49
00:06:00,454 --> 00:06:02,637
It's the doubt that stops you doing something.

50
00:06:04,901 --> 00:06:06,944
We'll come to that another time maybe.

51
00:06:07,485 --> 00:06:09,346
Clinging to mere rules and ritual.

52
00:06:10,588 --> 00:06:12,932
And then there's sensuous craving, ill will.

53
00:06:14,213 --> 00:06:19,401
And then there's craving for fine material existence and fine immaterial existence.

54
00:06:19,422 --> 00:06:20,442
That's number six and seven.

55
00:06:20,704 --> 00:06:22,646
So those are the jhanas, the absorptions.

56
00:06:24,009 --> 00:06:24,930
Then there's conceit.

57
00:06:25,089 --> 00:06:25,971
That's a big fetter.

58
00:06:26,793 --> 00:06:27,112
I am.

59
00:06:27,750 --> 00:06:32,795
It's how you finish that sentence is your conceit.

60
00:06:33,076 --> 00:06:33,435
I am.

61
00:06:34,396 --> 00:06:34,656
See?

62
00:06:35,899 --> 00:06:38,420
And then finally, sorry, then there's restlessness.

63
00:06:38,581 --> 00:06:47,949
So this refers to any leftover agitation from the defilements and, of course, ignorance.

64
00:06:47,970 --> 00:06:50,471
So we'll come to them in the fullness of time.

65
00:06:51,192 --> 00:06:56,997
So here he's asking Malunkiaputta, what do you remember of the lower fetters as taught by me?

66
00:06:57,721 --> 00:07:16,559
And he replies, I remember it's translated as personality view, but it's basically identity as a lower fetter, doubt as a lower fetter, adherence to rules and observances as a lower fetter, sensual desire as a lower fetter.

67
00:07:16,798 --> 00:07:20,382
And I remember ill will as a lower fetter taught by the Blessed One.

68
00:07:21,043 --> 00:07:26,427
It is in this way, Venerable Sir, that I remember the five lower fetters taught by the Blessed One.

69
00:07:27,067 --> 00:07:33,475
Now, without the commentaries, we wouldn't actually know, wouldn't actually understand the Buddha's reply.

70
00:07:35,317 --> 00:07:50,677
What the commentary says is that the Buddha, from this, or in, I mean, this is only a resume, really, of the conversation, has understood Malonkyaputta to say that these fetters only arise here and now, okay?

71
00:07:50,697 --> 00:07:52,761
Only arise on occasion.

72
00:07:53,983 --> 00:07:55,605
So this is what he says.

73
00:07:56,733 --> 00:08:02,139
To whom do you remember my having taught the five fetters, the five law fetters that way?

74
00:08:04,202 --> 00:08:08,747
Would not the wanderers of other sex confute you with the simile of an infant?

75
00:08:09,730 --> 00:08:15,596
For a young tender infant lying prone does not even have the notion of self-personality.

76
00:08:16,317 --> 00:08:18,940
So how could personality view arise in him?

77
00:08:19,802 --> 00:08:26,571
Yet the underlying tendency of two personality view lies within him.

78
00:08:28,019 --> 00:08:32,523
A young tender infant lying prone does not even have the notion of teachings.

79
00:08:32,842 --> 00:08:36,927
So how could doubt about the teachings arise in him?

80
00:08:36,947 --> 00:08:41,931
Yet the underlying tendency to doubt lies within him.

81
00:08:41,951 --> 00:08:46,916
A young tender infant lying prone does not even have the notion of rules.

82
00:08:47,216 --> 00:08:51,559
So how could adherence to rules and observations arise in him?

83
00:08:51,980 --> 00:08:57,705
Yet the underlying tendency to adhere to rules and observation lies in him.

84
00:08:58,158 --> 00:09:04,587
And then, of course, he says the very same thing about desire, sinful desire and ill will.

85
00:09:07,773 --> 00:09:16,645
So then Ananda steps in and says, blessed one, it is time, sublime one, for the blessed one to teach the five law fetters.

86
00:09:16,745 --> 00:09:21,734
So although he's talked about it before, he obviously needs to talk about it again.

87
00:09:22,355 --> 00:09:25,299
Then listen, Ananda, and attend closely to what I say.

88
00:09:26,081 --> 00:09:26,881
Yes, venerable sir.

89
00:09:28,177 --> 00:09:49,206
So now here he says, an untaught ordinary person who has no regard for the noble ones and is unskilled and undisciplined in their Dharma, who has no regard for true men and is unskilled in their Dharma, abides with a mind obsessed and enslaved by identity view.

90
00:09:50,107 --> 00:09:57,577
And he does not understand as it is, as it actually is, the escape from a risen identity view.

91
00:09:58,638 --> 00:10:07,591
And when that identity view has become habitual and is uneradicated in him, it is a lower fetter.

92
00:10:08,711 --> 00:10:19,988
He abides with the mind, obsessed and enslaved with doubt, rules and observations, sensual desire, obsession and ill will.

93
00:10:20,524 --> 00:10:29,657
And when that ill will has become habitual and uneradicated in him, it is a lot better.

94
00:10:35,225 --> 00:10:37,508
And then he says, of course, there is an escape.

95
00:10:37,607 --> 00:10:39,951
That's his usual way of doing it.

96
00:10:40,812 --> 00:10:44,638
For the underlying tendency is abandoned in him.

97
00:10:46,200 --> 00:10:50,024
So what we have here is the Buddha telling us that

98
00:10:50,461 --> 00:11:02,153
At an obvious level, these fetters, unwholesomenesses, arise through our speech, through our actions, etc.

99
00:11:04,255 --> 00:11:08,360
But even when they don't, the tendency is there within us.

100
00:11:09,422 --> 00:11:10,923
So that's an underlying thing.

101
00:11:11,203 --> 00:11:14,668
There are, in fact, three levels of that.

102
00:11:15,388 --> 00:11:19,572
The first one is called anusaya, which is a latent tendency.

103
00:11:20,043 --> 00:11:28,611
Now, in the discourses, they're not actually enumerated, but they were later, especially in the Abhidhamma, the higher teaching.

104
00:11:29,673 --> 00:11:33,076
And then the next part is that they obsess the mind.

105
00:11:33,717 --> 00:11:37,923
And then, of course, they express themselves in what we say and do.

106
00:11:38,082 --> 00:11:39,544
So those are the three things.

107
00:11:39,605 --> 00:11:39,825
Right.

108
00:11:40,426 --> 00:11:42,567
And of course, it's occasion that brings them out.

109
00:11:43,008 --> 00:11:44,429
It's an occasion that brings them out.

110
00:11:44,748 --> 00:11:51,219
We find ourselves falling into some sensual desire when the object of sensual desire arises.

111
00:11:51,620 --> 00:11:54,904
Otherwise, it won't manifest, but it's there as a potential.

112
00:11:58,311 --> 00:11:58,471
Okay?

113
00:12:02,216 --> 00:12:03,919
Again, he gives us some similes.

114
00:12:04,380 --> 00:12:09,168
Just as when a great tree standing possessed of heartwood, that's the inner part,

115
00:12:09,722 --> 00:12:37,822
it is not possible that anyone shall cut out its heartwood without cutting through its bark and sapling so too there is a path that is that that we can't get on until we process of training uh and then of course he says that that that's possible okay uh he then talks about um

116
00:12:38,004 --> 00:12:44,030
Suppose the river Ganges were full of water right up to the brim so that crows could drink from it.

117
00:12:44,532 --> 00:12:54,081
And then a feeble man came thinking by swimming across the stream with my arms, I shall get safely across the further shore.

118
00:12:54,542 --> 00:13:00,347
Remember, the further shore is always a metaphor for Libana.

119
00:13:00,368 --> 00:13:03,090
Yet he would not be able to get safely across.

120
00:13:04,371 --> 00:13:06,813
So when the Dharma is being taught to someone,

121
00:13:07,115 --> 00:13:10,480
for the ending of the cessation of identity.

122
00:13:11,240 --> 00:13:19,111
If his mind does not enter into it and acquire steadiness, confidence and decision, then he can be regarded as a feeble man.

123
00:13:19,351 --> 00:13:31,528
In other words, this has to be truly investigated by us through the process of vipassana, but also just any time of the day, the notion of investigating who I am might arise.

124
00:13:33,552 --> 00:13:36,395
And of course, he says the opposite of someone who is strong.

125
00:13:37,321 --> 00:14:00,932
uh so uh abandoning unwholesome state quiet uh quietly secluded from central pleasure etc and in this particular case he takes us through the absorptions now uh just before we we go on to the last bit um

126
00:14:01,856 --> 00:14:04,861
It's good just to go through these fetters.

127
00:14:05,241 --> 00:14:11,772
So a fetter, a shackle, a chain, is what's keeping us to this form of existence.

128
00:14:12,653 --> 00:14:16,600
So one of the definitions of nibbana is to be unshackled.

129
00:14:16,980 --> 00:14:28,017
It's an awareness, the sati, which is unshackled, liberated from its delusion with the world, its illusion with the world.

130
00:14:28,638 --> 00:14:41,918
So we have this personality belief, that deep identity with the human being, with our psychophysical organism, with all our thoughts, with all our relationships, etc.

131
00:14:42,961 --> 00:14:47,908
Skeptical doubt is this particular doubt which stops us doing things.

132
00:14:49,410 --> 00:14:53,397
I'm sure you probably have a memory of being at the public baths.

133
00:14:53,629 --> 00:15:05,028
and climbing on the diving board and getting right up to the top one and not having the confidence to jump until somebody pushed you and then after that it was dead easy.

134
00:15:07,131 --> 00:15:17,950
So skeptical doubt, doubting ourselves, unable to meditate properly and all that, doubting the Buddha's teaching and doubting the teacher.

135
00:15:18,232 --> 00:15:36,342
won't say anything about that so it's a case of skeptical doubt stopping us doing something it becomes a it becomes a barrier even in ordinary daily life if you take you know if you apply for a job but you doubt if you can do it doubt then you you never you never go for the interview

136
00:15:39,293 --> 00:15:50,261
Mere rules and regulations or mere rules and ritual ceremonies, the mistake is that they are actually, shall we say, important to the path.

137
00:15:50,682 --> 00:15:53,105
But no, they're just aids to the path.

138
00:15:53,705 --> 00:16:08,557
When we take refuges and precepts, for instance, or when we light candles, they're sort of like a background which helps us to establish the right sort of atmosphere, the right sort of attention within us.

139
00:16:08,892 --> 00:16:18,202
They're just aids, really, but in themselves are, of course, useless in attaining liberation as such.

140
00:16:20,426 --> 00:16:23,509
In those days, there would have been lots of rituals to get what you want.

141
00:16:24,892 --> 00:16:27,735
The belief in ritual would have been very strong.

142
00:16:27,754 --> 00:16:30,798
And of course, it still is in some religions.

143
00:16:35,048 --> 00:16:41,216
Now, those three go when we enter the stream, right?

144
00:16:41,275 --> 00:16:42,136
The Sotapanna.

145
00:16:42,597 --> 00:16:45,881
So remember, there are four levels of attainment.

146
00:16:46,381 --> 00:17:03,604
The first one being that insight into one of the three characteristics, either not self, that everything we're aware of is not me, not mine, and itself is not a self.

147
00:17:04,208 --> 00:17:11,894
Impermanence, that also will help us to enter the stream, to see that everything actually does perish, does come to an end.

148
00:17:12,516 --> 00:17:14,778
There is no continuity.

149
00:17:16,078 --> 00:17:22,444
And the third one is dukkha, suffering, and that's really seeing how we create suffering.

150
00:17:22,925 --> 00:17:26,469
It's a direct understanding of the role of desire.

151
00:17:27,931 --> 00:17:30,553
And those insights have to be deep enough

152
00:17:30,954 --> 00:17:35,359
to have a change, to bring about a change in our lives.

153
00:17:37,962 --> 00:17:41,567
So that's this, those are the first three fetters, as they're known.

154
00:17:42,848 --> 00:17:49,496
By the way, that first insight that person might have into not-self, it's a change of view.

155
00:17:50,017 --> 00:17:52,819
The sense of self is still very strong.

156
00:17:53,340 --> 00:17:59,847
And often people doubt whether they've had that insight because the sense of self still remains very strong.

157
00:18:00,605 --> 00:18:06,352
but the actual view has been changed or the insight has broken the illusion.

158
00:18:08,314 --> 00:18:21,189
I mean, the example I normally use is about smoking because when my father smoked, you know, pre-Second World War, 1940s, 50s, it wasn't considered to be particularly harmful.

159
00:18:21,609 --> 00:18:28,417
But as the science finally got through, when the tobacco companies finally admitted that they'd been

160
00:18:28,803 --> 00:18:36,354
fooling everybody, deluding everybody, everybody began to understand that smoking is really, really bad for your health.

161
00:18:37,095 --> 00:18:38,336
But it didn't stop them smoking.

162
00:18:38,737 --> 00:18:40,619
The obsession was still there.

163
00:18:41,280 --> 00:18:46,208
The view was changed, but the desire to smoke had not been undermined.

164
00:18:46,949 --> 00:18:57,222
It's surprising how when some people actually had the consequence of that, I'm thinking particularly of a father of one of my friends who had a heart attack,

165
00:18:57,523 --> 00:19:17,777
smoked all his life had a heart attack and after that completely stopped a bit later now the next two the sensual uh the sensuous craving uh craving that arises on all the senses including the inner sense of the mind whatever the mind is offering our dreams our fantasies etc

166
00:19:18,414 --> 00:19:26,423
And all the ill will, all the negativity that's in us, they are only attenuated.

167
00:19:26,462 --> 00:19:30,027
They're only undermined with the second path.

168
00:19:30,047 --> 00:19:35,452
And they lose their power with the third path.

169
00:19:35,472 --> 00:19:42,599
And what that really is saying is that the attraction of the sensual world is no longer there for somebody who's a non-returner.

170
00:19:43,255 --> 00:19:51,686
So the second path is called a once returner, suggesting that you have to come back for a bit more suffering on this to another rebirth.

171
00:19:52,488 --> 00:20:03,323
But the one who has broken through the delusion of seeking happiness in the sensual world, they don't have to come back to this form of existence.

172
00:20:04,644 --> 00:20:10,932
They can be reborn in a particular heaven, it is said, where they attain full liberation.

173
00:20:12,904 --> 00:20:35,711
And then the final ones, the craving for material and immaterial existence, that's really to do with these absorptions, which are in themselves very delightful, beautiful places to be, and often in some, especially the fine immaterial ones, can be mistaken for Nibbana.

174
00:20:35,731 --> 00:20:42,000
The conceit of I am, remember, disappears, that comes right at the end,

175
00:20:42,132 --> 00:20:43,934
the breaking of that conceit.

176
00:20:45,297 --> 00:20:47,220
And then restlessness is always there.

177
00:20:47,319 --> 00:20:54,090
That's the little bits of agitation that's left from old habits that the person has had.

178
00:20:55,333 --> 00:20:58,637
And then finally, undermining ignorance as such.

179
00:20:59,159 --> 00:21:03,465
And that suggests, of course, that they know what or who they really are.

180
00:21:04,047 --> 00:21:05,368
The Buddha within.

181
00:21:05,888 --> 00:21:08,173
That's the moment of complete liberation.

182
00:21:12,186 --> 00:21:18,500
So that takes us through the ten fetters.

183
00:21:24,230 --> 00:21:31,224
So this is whatever exists therein of feeling, perception,

184
00:21:31,576 --> 00:21:33,640
habits and consciousness.

185
00:21:34,121 --> 00:21:51,255
He sees these states as impermanent and suffering, as a disease, as a tumor, as a barb, as a calamity, as an affliction, as alien, as disintegrating, as void, in other words, empty, insubstantial, as not self.

186
00:21:51,926 --> 00:21:57,796
He turns his mind away from those states and directs them to the deathless element.

187
00:21:58,196 --> 00:21:59,659
That's really confusing, isn't it?

188
00:22:00,240 --> 00:22:05,207
I mean, what does that mean, direct them to the deathless element?

189
00:22:07,210 --> 00:22:18,507
It's a way, remember, of the Buddha pointing out that there is something which is not phenomenal, something that doesn't belong to the mind, etc., etc.

190
00:22:19,067 --> 00:22:20,230
Now, how do we do that?

191
00:22:20,580 --> 00:22:24,066
You can't obviously see Nibbana.

192
00:22:24,086 --> 00:22:30,997
If we were to be able to see or experience Nibbana as an object, then of course it would be conditioned.

193
00:22:31,396 --> 00:22:32,598
So it can't be that.

194
00:22:32,900 --> 00:22:34,261
It's not looking at that.

195
00:22:34,821 --> 00:22:44,277
What he's saying is to turn away from that desire to involve ourselves in the world and to pull ourselves away.

196
00:22:44,616 --> 00:22:49,845
So that's why when we're in that position within ourselves of the objective observer,

197
00:22:50,398 --> 00:23:20,253
when we've accessed that observation post to recognize that there is that distance there is that separation that everything we're observing is an object and then of course to realize that the very sense of self the observer is an object so we can't be that and uh and it's just a case of remaining in that position which is uh beginning to see the deathless okay

198
00:23:23,676 --> 00:23:29,723
And when we're in that state, we can always ask ourselves, what's it like?

199
00:23:29,903 --> 00:23:39,095
What's it like being the observer where there is no body, no physicality, where there is no emotion, where there is no thought?

200
00:23:40,217 --> 00:23:48,807
This comes to us usually at some time on a retreat, but even in ordinary daily life, depending on

201
00:23:49,022 --> 00:23:59,704
what's happened during the day, as long as you're calm, as long as you can get concentrated, as long as you can lift yourself up to that position, you can always ask yourself, what's it like being this observer?

202
00:24:00,385 --> 00:24:09,444
Because that's what we mean when we say those who are mindful are in the presence, in the vicinity of, in the presence of Nibbana.

203
00:24:12,428 --> 00:24:25,480
And just that little insight tells us that this is peaceful, it's sublime, the stilling of all formations, all habits, the relinquishing of attachments, the destruction of craving, dispassion, cessation.

204
00:24:26,200 --> 00:24:33,666
That's the ending of the world as a place where we're going to find happiness and nibbana.

205
00:24:35,568 --> 00:24:38,611
And this is, of course, right at the end of the whole process.

206
00:24:38,651 --> 00:24:40,613
This is when we become fully liberated.

207
00:24:41,352 --> 00:24:45,115
And standing upon that, he attains the destruction of the taints.

208
00:24:45,135 --> 00:24:45,376
See?

209
00:24:46,557 --> 00:24:49,981
But he does not attain the destruction of the taints.

210
00:24:50,742 --> 00:25:08,423
So if he doesn't attain the destruction of the taints then, then he says, because of that desire for the Dharma, the delight in the Dharma, with the destruction of the five lower fetters, then he becomes one due to reappear spontaneously.

211
00:25:09,009 --> 00:25:15,619
and there in the pure abodes and there attain final nirvana without ever returning to this world.

212
00:25:16,300 --> 00:25:20,125
This is the path, the way to abandoning the five law fetters.

213
00:25:26,776 --> 00:25:30,682
And then here's a real, here's the clincher at the end, you see.

214
00:25:31,262 --> 00:25:37,531
So Ananda says, Venerable Sir, if this is the path, the way to abandoning the five law fetters,

215
00:25:37,798 --> 00:25:45,337
then how is it that some bhikkhus here gain deliverance of mind and some gain deliverance by wisdom?

216
00:25:46,039 --> 00:25:52,517
Now, gain deliverance by mind is through these jhanas.

217
00:25:53,037 --> 00:25:54,778
and the purity of the mind.

218
00:25:54,838 --> 00:25:56,421
But then, of course, there has to be insight.

219
00:25:56,921 --> 00:26:00,664
And there are some who are delivered just through insight.

220
00:26:00,904 --> 00:26:02,606
So that's the vipassana only way.

221
00:26:03,327 --> 00:26:08,252
And the answer is the difference, Ananda, is in their faculties, in how they are.

222
00:26:10,635 --> 00:26:17,083
And, of course, the Venerable Ananda was satisfied and delighted in the Blessed One's words, as I'm hoping we are too.

223
00:26:17,943 --> 00:26:22,909
So I hope this is, shall we say...

224
00:26:23,377 --> 00:26:41,182
describe the fetters well enough for you to understand them and it gives us pointers and that of course you're not confused by it all and that I trust that you will devote your meditations to investigating the fetters.

225
00:26:43,568 --> 00:26:46,415
May you be fully liberated.

